WEBVTT

00:01.084 --> 00:05.297
Lainey: <i>Back in the '90s,</i>
<i>one of the biggest toy fads</i>
<i>was Beanie Babies.</i>

00:05.297 --> 00:06.840
<i>These cute little</i>
<i>stuffed animals took</i>
<i>the world by storm.</i>

00:06.840 --> 00:09.092
<i>People would flock</i>
<i>to shopping malls in a mad dash</i>

00:09.092 --> 00:10.511
<i>to collect as many</i>
<i>as they could,</i>

00:10.511 --> 00:12.888
<i>and they were especially</i>
<i>popular at William Penn.</i>

00:12.888 --> 00:13.889
What's your poison?

00:13.889 --> 00:15.015
I need Claude the Crab.

00:15.015 --> 00:16.767
That'll cost you $40.
Johnny: Hey!

00:16.767 --> 00:19.102
You know there's no dealing
Beanies on school grounds.

00:19.102 --> 00:21.104
Beat it
before I tell Glascott.

00:21.104 --> 00:23.941
I got Claude the Crab
for $30.

00:23.941 --> 00:25.776
That's right, suckers.

00:25.776 --> 00:27.361
You're looking
at a first‐edition

00:27.361 --> 00:29.613
mint‐condition
Patti the Platty!

00:29.613 --> 00:32.032
I did a lot of things
I'm not proud of to
get this Beanie Baby.

00:32.032 --> 00:33.575
You do know you're drooling
over a bag of beans,

00:33.575 --> 00:34.660
and you're also adults?

00:34.660 --> 00:36.036
Says the guy
who loves Tamagotchis,

00:36.036 --> 00:37.538
Furbys, Koosh balls...

00:37.538 --> 00:39.122
"Harry Potter,"
"Goosebumps"...

00:39.122 --> 00:40.958
Pokémon,
Magic: The Gathering...

00:40.958 --> 00:42.960
Pogs, man. Pogs?
Oh, come on!

00:42.960 --> 00:45.587
It says right there
on the Pog package
"fun for all ages."

00:45.587 --> 00:47.548
But this whole Beanie Baby
craze? Don't get it.

00:47.548 --> 00:48.924
Lainey: But they're
so cute and cuddly.

00:48.924 --> 00:50.342
Uh, look, don't touch.

00:50.342 --> 00:52.010
Because, you know,
your hands are gross.

00:52.010 --> 00:54.304
Any way you'd...
part with Patti?

00:54.304 --> 00:56.223
Come on.
How much we talking?

00:56.223 --> 00:57.391
<i>You</i> collect
these things, too?

00:57.391 --> 00:59.559
Collect? No.
I flip 'em.

00:59.559 --> 01:01.937
Buy low, sell high,
reap the rewards.

01:01.937 --> 01:04.189
Above‐ground pool,
here I come!

01:04.189 --> 01:06.316
These things double in value
every day.

01:06.316 --> 01:07.693
Ask Warren Buffett.

01:07.693 --> 01:10.404
He'll tell you ‐‐
sell stocks, buy beanies.

01:10.404 --> 01:12.823
You're all fools.
I know, right?

01:12.823 --> 01:14.700
What I mean is,
there's a 100% chance

01:14.700 --> 01:17.744
that one day we'll all be living
in a post‐apocalyptic world

01:17.744 --> 01:20.872
where Beanie Babies are
the only form of legal tender.

01:20.872 --> 01:23.542
Do I sound this stupid
talking about all the
weird stuff that <i>I</i> like?

01:23.542 --> 01:25.919
You'll be a believer when
you're scavenging for scraps

01:25.919 --> 01:27.921
and I live like a king ‐‐

01:27.921 --> 01:29.798
trading Pinchers the Lobster

01:29.798 --> 01:32.676
for matches, seeds,
and ice‐cold drinking water.

01:32.676 --> 01:33.635
Do you seriously
believe that?

01:33.635 --> 01:35.095
Oh, I do.

01:35.095 --> 01:36.888
It's the only way
I can justify spending $600

01:36.888 --> 01:39.933
on a bean‐stuffed crustacean
in an eBay bidding war.

01:39.933 --> 01:40.809
Lainey: Can I pet it?

01:42.728 --> 01:45.772
♪ One of these days,
you're gonna get outta here ♪

01:45.772 --> 01:48.692
♪ Live your life
and finally be free ♪

01:48.692 --> 01:51.653
♪ Go where you wanna go,
do what you wanna do ♪

01:51.653 --> 01:55.073
♪ Someday, you will say
"Those were the days" ♪

01:55.073 --> 01:57.284
<i>It was December 11th,</i>
<i>1990‐something,</i>

01:57.284 --> 01:59.578
<i>and Wilma was about to discover</i>
<i>a holiday surprise.</i>

01:59.578 --> 02:01.621
Well, I'll be damned!

02:01.621 --> 02:04.291
♪♪

02:04.291 --> 02:05.584
It's happening.

02:05.584 --> 02:07.252
It's happening!

02:07.252 --> 02:09.254
Look what's on the card shelves
this year.

02:09.254 --> 02:10.964
Kwanzaa?
That's right.

02:10.964 --> 02:12.883
And as we all know,
once we make it to Hallmark,

02:12.883 --> 02:14.718
that means we're official!

02:14.718 --> 02:15.927
Move over, Santa.

02:15.927 --> 02:18.263
If you <i>can,</i>
you fat sack of garbage.

02:18.263 --> 02:19.848
Whoa! Whoa!
Whoa!

02:19.848 --> 02:22.434
I'm sorry, but come on.
Kwanzaa?

02:22.434 --> 02:26.313
Oh. I'm Jehovah's Witness,
so we really don't do holidays.

02:26.313 --> 02:28.482
What is your problem, man?
Why do you got to
ruin stuff, Coop?

02:28.482 --> 02:29.691
Ooh, you know what?

02:29.691 --> 02:31.276
We should add it
to the Christmas concert.

02:31.276 --> 02:32.736
It'll be a good way
to teach people

02:32.736 --> 02:33.862
what Kwanzaa's all about.

02:33.862 --> 02:35.072
You know,
I think it'd be great

02:35.072 --> 02:36.698
to put some new life
into our holiday show.

02:36.698 --> 02:38.867
We've been doing the
same, old script since
I went to school here.

02:38.867 --> 02:40.160
And lucky for us,
we have

02:40.160 --> 02:42.537
a semi‐professional
script writer on faculty.

02:42.537 --> 02:44.748
Who?
Dear God!
Do not ask.

02:44.748 --> 02:45.791
Too late. She asked.

02:45.791 --> 02:47.668
Screenplay, you ask?

02:47.668 --> 02:49.878
Why, yes.
I'll tell you all about it.

02:51.171 --> 02:52.464
"Sole Brothers"?

02:52.464 --> 02:54.424
Yeah, it's the story
of Jeffrey Sole

02:54.424 --> 02:57.260
and his identical twin,
David Alan Brothers.

02:57.260 --> 03:00.013
They're shoe salesmen
who moonlight as detectives.

03:00.013 --> 03:03.141
If they're twin brothers, why do
they have different last names?

03:03.141 --> 03:04.059
Okay, we're good.
No more questions.

03:04.059 --> 03:05.143
Sorry.
I got to know.

03:05.143 --> 03:06.978
Why the hell
is there a genie lamp?

03:06.978 --> 03:08.397
You know what?
It's better if I pitch it.

03:08.397 --> 03:09.981
Do not pitch it!
Fade in.

03:09.981 --> 03:13.402
Exterior ‐‐ Arabian Desert.
Dead of night.

03:13.402 --> 03:15.278
Camels walking ‐‐
Yeah, I've heard enough.

03:15.278 --> 03:17.322
Lainey, <i>you're</i> writing
about Kwanzaa.

03:17.322 --> 03:19.491
Um, are you sure
it should be me?

03:19.491 --> 03:21.618
You know, because
I'm, like...you know...

03:21.618 --> 03:23.954
and people who celebrate
Kwanzaa are, um...

03:23.954 --> 03:25.789
you know,
they're, um...

03:25.789 --> 03:27.207
So, you know...
[ Chuckles ]

03:27.207 --> 03:29.084
Okay, what is going on
with you right now?

03:29.084 --> 03:30.961
Whenever I talk about
this kind of thing, I'm just,

03:30.961 --> 03:32.963
you know, like, worried
I'm gonna say the wrong thing.

03:32.963 --> 03:35.048
What exactly do you think
you're gonna say?

03:35.048 --> 03:36.758
Oh, God! Nothing!

03:36.758 --> 03:39.094
But...yeah,
John should take charge.

03:39.094 --> 03:40.387
Kwanzaa's all yours.

03:40.387 --> 03:41.930
Not that I won't be there
to support it,

03:41.930 --> 03:43.765
'cause I <i>do</i> support it ‐‐
a lot.

03:43.765 --> 03:46.351
But not <i>too</i> much. I don't want
to overstep my bounds.

03:46.351 --> 03:47.644
Just the appropriate amount
of supporting.

03:47.644 --> 03:48.437
Lainey.
Yes?

03:48.437 --> 03:49.855
Please stop.
Stopping.

03:49.855 --> 03:51.773
<i>While I was awkwardly</i>
<i>getting into Kwanzaa,</i>

03:51.773 --> 03:52.899
<i>my new roommate, CB,</i>

03:52.899 --> 03:54.860
<i>was getting into</i>
<i>the holiday spirit.</i>

03:54.860 --> 03:58.029
Dude! You cleaned
my entire place <i>and</i> got
me a Christmas tree?

03:58.029 --> 03:59.739
Why do you keep doing
stuff like this?

03:59.739 --> 04:01.992
Well, 'cause my place
burned down and you
took me in rent‐free,

04:01.992 --> 04:03.493
and cleaning
helps me forget

04:03.493 --> 04:05.454
my place burned down
and you took me in rent‐free.

04:05.454 --> 04:06.204
Aw, man.

04:06.204 --> 04:07.456
If I knew I had a tree,

04:07.456 --> 04:08.748
I wouldn't have opened
Barry's gift already.

04:08.748 --> 04:10.292
Barry: <i>Hi, baby.</i>

04:10.292 --> 04:12.878
<i>I'm</i> fishing <i>you</i>
<i>a Merry Christmas.</i>

04:12.878 --> 04:15.213
I've been listening
to bad fish puns all day.

04:15.213 --> 04:17.466
Are you sure you want to keep
that in a place of prominence?

04:17.466 --> 04:19.259
<i>I am</i> fin <i>love with you.</i>

04:19.259 --> 04:20.760
Yeah.
It's just so Barry.

04:20.760 --> 04:22.804
<i>Look!</i>
<i>I'm a Barry‐cuda. Ha!</i>

04:22.804 --> 04:24.681
You mean
loud and intrusive?
Stop.

04:24.681 --> 04:26.600
You just have to get
to know him, and then
you'll see what I see.

04:26.600 --> 04:28.059
Why the fish?

04:28.059 --> 04:29.811
'Cause you've been
dropping him hints all month

04:29.811 --> 04:31.688
that you wanted
that platypus Beanie Baby.

04:31.688 --> 04:34.065
Eh, it's disappointing,
but they're really hard to find,

04:34.065 --> 04:35.692
and this just
screams "Barry."

04:35.692 --> 04:38.111
<i>My name's Barry,</i>
<i>and I'm a fish!</i>

04:38.111 --> 04:39.780
Come on.
Don't make excuses for the guy.

04:39.780 --> 04:41.406
You deserve
that Beanie Baby.

04:41.406 --> 04:43.658
Well, my birthday's in a month,
so maybe he'll be my hero then

04:43.658 --> 04:44.868
and get me
that new Beanie Baby.

04:44.868 --> 04:47.370
♪♪

04:47.370 --> 04:49.122
Yo, Coop!

04:49.122 --> 04:50.332
Hey, man,
you got a sec?

04:50.332 --> 04:52.042
I need some help translating
this Spanish verse

04:52.042 --> 04:54.336
for my poetry class.
Sure!

04:54.336 --> 04:56.630
It's nice to know you
want to talk to me about
something other than Lainey.

04:56.630 --> 04:57.714
[ Both chuckle ]

04:57.714 --> 04:58.882
So, what's up?

04:58.882 --> 05:00.091
It's about Lainey.

05:00.091 --> 05:01.343
Oh, come on, man!

05:01.343 --> 05:03.178
I finally found a way
to win her heart ‐‐

05:03.178 --> 05:04.888
Beanie Babies.

05:04.888 --> 05:06.473
Please unlock the door.
I'm scared.

05:06.473 --> 05:07.891
Just listen for one sec.

05:07.891 --> 05:09.267
Living with Lainey
made me realize

05:09.267 --> 05:10.894
how perfect we are
for each other,

05:10.894 --> 05:13.271
and once I get her
a Patti the Platypus,
<i>she'll</i> see it, too.

05:13.271 --> 05:15.273
[ Sighs ] Seriously?

05:15.273 --> 05:17.359
You think your way in
is a Beanie Baby?

05:17.359 --> 05:19.528
It's not the Beanie itself
that wins her over.

05:19.528 --> 05:20.737
It's what the Beanie
represents.

05:20.737 --> 05:21.863
Which is?

05:21.863 --> 05:23.198
That Barry's
all wrong for her.

05:23.198 --> 05:24.491
For some reason,
Lainey thinks

05:24.491 --> 05:26.326
that he's some special,
amazing guy, when, really,

05:26.326 --> 05:28.328
he's a spazzy goofus
who bought her a talking fish.

05:28.328 --> 05:29.496
But not CB.

05:29.496 --> 05:31.581
Just one problem
with your plan, though.

05:31.581 --> 05:33.750
No one can get their hands
on that platypus.

05:33.750 --> 05:35.335
<i>I</i> can.

05:35.335 --> 05:37.087
There's a Beanie Baby drop
going down

05:37.087 --> 05:38.880
in Willow Grove,
8:00 a. m. sharp.

05:38.880 --> 05:41.007
I'm gonna camp out overnight
so I can be first in line,

05:41.007 --> 05:42.717
'cause you're gonna cover
my last two classes

05:42.717 --> 05:44.553
and run
my after‐school book club

05:44.553 --> 05:47.055
and then drive Earl Ball home
'cause his Volvo's in the shop

05:47.055 --> 05:49.558
and then, in the morning,
just drive him downtown

05:49.558 --> 05:50.851
to pick up said Volvo
from the mechanic.

05:50.851 --> 05:52.644
Is that okay?

05:52.644 --> 05:54.729
Lainey: <i>While CB was hatching</i>
<i>his plan to win me over,</i>

05:54.729 --> 05:56.106
<i>I gathered up my students</i>

05:56.106 --> 05:57.858
<i>for Glascott's</i>
<i>big Kwanzaa announcement.</i>

05:57.858 --> 05:59.234
Okay, we're finally making

05:59.234 --> 06:01.069
this Christmas concert
all‐inclusive.

06:01.069 --> 06:04.197
That means we now cover
the weeklong celebration

06:04.197 --> 06:06.658
of African
and African‐American culture

06:06.658 --> 06:07.826
known as Kwanzaa.

06:07.826 --> 06:09.494
♪ Kwanzaa! ♪

06:09.494 --> 06:10.495
Don't do that.

06:10.495 --> 06:11.663
Kwanzaa.

06:11.663 --> 06:13.248
Sounds like a dude
from "Mortal Kombat."

06:13.248 --> 06:14.499
[ Both laugh ]

06:14.499 --> 06:15.500
That's enough.

06:15.500 --> 06:16.751
Alright.
Let's rehearse.

06:16.751 --> 06:18.962
Uh, Felicia,
you take the lead in this one.

06:18.962 --> 06:20.547
But I didn't even
raise my hand.

06:20.547 --> 06:22.424
Yep, part's all yours.

06:22.424 --> 06:24.217
I already have a part
in the nativity scene.

06:24.217 --> 06:25.677
Which I now
give to Marni.

06:25.677 --> 06:26.928
You can't do that.

06:26.928 --> 06:29.014
But I did.
It's done. Yay!

06:29.014 --> 06:30.640
♪ Kwanzaa! ♪
No.

06:30.640 --> 06:32.976
Can we, like,
talk in the hall right now?

06:32.976 --> 06:34.019
To the hall!

06:34.019 --> 06:35.020
I don't care
what you say.

06:35.020 --> 06:36.438
You can't
make me do this.

06:36.438 --> 06:37.981
Please!
It's really important.

06:37.981 --> 06:39.566
To <i>you,</i> maybe.

06:39.566 --> 06:41.192
But they're just
gonna laugh at me.

06:41.192 --> 06:42.611
And that's why it's your job
to teach them

06:42.611 --> 06:44.112
what Kwanzaa's all about.

06:44.112 --> 06:45.739
Why is it <i>my</i> job?

06:45.739 --> 06:46.948
I'm in high school.

06:46.948 --> 06:48.408
I just want to fly
under the radar

06:48.408 --> 06:49.701
and not embarrass myself.

06:49.701 --> 06:52.287
The fact that you find Kwanzaa
so embarrassing

06:52.287 --> 06:54.080
is the exact reason
that you're doing this.

06:54.080 --> 06:55.624
But ‐‐
No buts.

06:55.624 --> 06:58.043
We finally have
an all‐inclusive holiday show,

06:58.043 --> 06:59.669
and you need
to be proud of it.

06:59.669 --> 07:02.088
Oh, you are
such a hypocrite.
Excuse me?

07:02.088 --> 07:04.424
You're just excited
because now it includes <i>us.</i>

07:04.424 --> 07:07.010
What about Reza? You didn't add
anything about Diwali.

07:07.010 --> 07:08.219
Only 'cause
I haven't heard of it

07:08.219 --> 07:09.554
until this very second,

07:09.554 --> 07:11.973
but thank you very much,
because now it's in.

07:11.973 --> 07:13.767
You sure you want
to take this on?

07:13.767 --> 07:16.436
Squeezing four holidays
into one show is gonna be tough.

07:16.436 --> 07:18.813
You think I can't handle
four holidays?

07:18.813 --> 07:21.900
I have ideas for 16
"Sole Brothers" sequels.

07:21.900 --> 07:24.444
Do not pitch me your lame movie
right now!

07:24.444 --> 07:25.820
I mean it!
Fade in.

07:25.820 --> 07:27.238
No!
Nuclear submarine.

07:27.238 --> 07:28.573
It makes no sense.

07:28.573 --> 07:31.034
Stop!
We angle on
Naval Captain Jeffrey Sole

07:31.034 --> 07:32.285
Please! Come on!
...and his identical
twin brother

07:32.285 --> 07:33.578
David Alan Brothers.

07:33.578 --> 07:34.621
Fine!

07:34.621 --> 07:37.332
I will do Kwanzaa.

07:37.332 --> 07:39.542
But mark my words,
you will regret it.

07:39.542 --> 07:42.545
Thank you. And I'm choosing
to ignore that threat.

07:42.545 --> 07:44.756
And, again, if you would
just read the screenplay...
[ Scoffs ]

07:44.756 --> 07:47.300
...it explains in flashbacks
how they can be brothers.

07:47.300 --> 07:49.886
<i>As Glascott got Felicia</i>
<i>to join his quest for Kwanzaa,</i>

07:49.886 --> 07:52.514
<i>CB was ready to battle</i>
<i>for my Beanie Baby.</i>

07:52.514 --> 07:54.015
You got this, Chucky.

07:54.015 --> 07:56.059
Get the Beanie,
be the hero.

07:56.059 --> 07:57.977
Get the Beanie,
be the hero.

07:57.977 --> 08:00.188
[ Survivor's "Eye of the Tiger"
plays ]
[ Shouting ]

08:01.940 --> 08:03.483
Elite athlete
coming through, baby!

08:03.483 --> 08:04.442
Rick?!

08:04.442 --> 08:05.819
[ Grunts ]

08:05.819 --> 08:07.779
[ Music slows, stops ]

08:07.779 --> 08:08.947
[ Sighs ]

08:08.947 --> 08:10.740
Come back, you animals.

08:10.740 --> 08:12.033
I got you.
[ Grunts ]

08:12.033 --> 08:13.326
Thank you.

08:13.326 --> 08:14.828
Rick, what are you
even doing here?

08:14.828 --> 08:16.287
Coop told me
you were camped out in line,

08:16.287 --> 08:18.748
which reminded me I had to snag
a Christmas present for Toby.

08:18.748 --> 08:20.125
But I waited all night.

08:20.125 --> 08:22.252
How do you arrive last
and then beat everyone?

08:22.252 --> 08:24.087
Took years of hard work,
CB.

08:24.087 --> 08:25.630
You see,
when I was but a boy,

08:25.630 --> 08:28.258
I wandered into my local gym
for the first time.

08:28.258 --> 08:29.467
There, I saw ‐‐
Yeah, I don't need
to hear the whole story.

08:29.467 --> 08:31.261
Please tell me
you grabbed a spare platypus.

08:31.261 --> 08:33.179
Oh, Toby's
over Beanie Babies.

08:33.179 --> 08:35.098
Instead, I got him
this bad boy.

08:35.098 --> 08:36.141
Turbo Man?

08:36.141 --> 08:37.767
[ Chuckling ]
The hell is that?

08:37.767 --> 08:40.311
Only the coolest action figure
of the year,

08:40.311 --> 08:42.981
as seen in the upcoming holiday
hit "Jingle All the Way."

08:42.981 --> 08:44.232
Yeah, I don't know
about that, man.

08:44.232 --> 08:45.442
Hello?

08:45.442 --> 08:47.527
It stars Arnold Schwarzenegger
<i>and</i> Sinbad.

08:47.527 --> 08:48.862
Okay, forget
about Turbo Man.

08:48.862 --> 08:50.905
I need your freakishly fast
roadrunner legs

08:50.905 --> 08:52.991
to get me that Beanie Baby
when the new shipment arrives.

08:52.991 --> 08:54.826
You want me to come <i>back</i>
to this madhouse?

08:54.826 --> 08:57.537
Here. Just take a Turbo Man.
There's a shocking amount left.

08:57.537 --> 08:59.330
I don't want Turbo Man.

08:59.330 --> 09:01.458
What about Lieutenant Dan Taylor
from "Forrest Gump"?

09:01.458 --> 09:02.709
No.

09:02.709 --> 09:04.335
"Cape Fear" ‐‐
fun for all ages.

09:04.335 --> 09:05.295
No.

09:05.295 --> 09:07.338
"Can't Hardly Wait" ‐‐
Seth Green?

09:07.338 --> 09:08.673
Again, no!

09:08.673 --> 09:09.966
"Troll 2"?
Seriously?

09:09.966 --> 09:11.301
"Ghost"?

09:11.301 --> 09:13.636
"Get off my train!"
Who makes these?

09:13.636 --> 09:15.805
[ As Matthew McConaughey ]
"Alright, alright, alright."

09:15.805 --> 09:17.432
Okay, please stop.

09:17.432 --> 09:19.225
It's got to be
Patti the Platypus, okay?

09:19.225 --> 09:20.769
I thought you hated
Beanie Babies.

09:20.769 --> 09:22.270
Okay, truth be told?

09:22.270 --> 09:23.688
I'm doing it for love.

09:23.688 --> 09:24.647
Love?

09:25.648 --> 09:27.025
I love love.

09:27.025 --> 09:28.318
This changes everything.

09:28.318 --> 09:29.694
Okay,
this might sound crazy,

09:29.694 --> 09:31.362
but if I get her
this Beanie Baby,

09:31.362 --> 09:33.656
maybe she'll see that <i>I'm</i>
the one who can make her happy.

09:33.656 --> 09:35.658
It <i>is</i> crazy.

09:35.658 --> 09:36.701
But so is love.

09:36.701 --> 09:38.036
Let's do this.

09:38.036 --> 09:39.537
<i>The next day,</i>
<i>Mellor and CB waited</i>

09:39.537 --> 09:40.830
<i>for another shot</i>
<i>at Patti the Platty,</i>

09:40.830 --> 09:42.415
<i>all in the name of love.</i>

09:42.415 --> 09:44.501
Oh, God. There's a bigger crowd
here than yesterday.

09:44.501 --> 09:46.711
Are you sure you can outrun
all these people?

09:46.711 --> 09:48.922
CB, look at me.

09:48.922 --> 09:51.174
I'm gonna get you
that bag of beans,

09:51.174 --> 09:54.010
and nothing ‐‐ <i>nothing</i> is gonna
stand in my way.

09:54.010 --> 09:55.095
Okay.

09:55.095 --> 09:56.179
What the ‐‐

09:56.179 --> 09:56.971
Barry?

09:58.431 --> 09:59.682
Hey!

09:59.682 --> 10:00.683
It's Coach and BJ!

10:00.683 --> 10:01.684
♪♪

10:04.145 --> 10:07.023
<i>Thanks to Felicia's defiance,</i>
<i>our Christmas concert</i>

10:07.023 --> 10:07.899
<i>was about to add</i>
<i>a few more holidays.</i>

10:07.899 --> 10:09.025
Okay, good news.

10:09.025 --> 10:10.485
Diwali has also
been added

10:10.485 --> 10:13.154
into our all‐inclusive
holiday show.

10:13.154 --> 10:14.405
Sounds good, Reza?

10:14.405 --> 10:15.406
Okay.

10:15.406 --> 10:16.825
♪ Diwali ♪

10:16.825 --> 10:18.284
Why don't you
take a walk?

10:18.284 --> 10:19.869
Walking.
Right.

10:19.869 --> 10:21.371
Okay. So, we're good.

10:21.371 --> 10:23.832
We got a little Kwanzaa,
we got some Diwali.

10:23.832 --> 10:26.084
[ Chuckles ] This is gonna be
the best holiday show ever.

10:26.084 --> 10:27.418
Uncle J?

10:27.418 --> 10:29.170
I actually did
some Internet surfing,

10:29.170 --> 10:31.798
and we are <i>far</i>
from all‐inclusive.

10:31.798 --> 10:35.176
Which is why I have a list
of other holidays, like, uh...

10:35.176 --> 10:39.222
The Feast of Seven Fishes,
St. Lucia, Boxing Day.

10:39.222 --> 10:41.391
[ Chuckling ] Boxing Day.
Awesome. I love "Rocky."

10:41.391 --> 10:42.851
[ As Sylvester Stallone ]
"Yo, Adrian."

10:42.851 --> 10:44.894
[ As Stallone ] Yo, Ronnie!
Consider all of it in!

10:44.894 --> 10:46.146
What about Krampus?

10:46.146 --> 10:47.188
[ Normal voice ]
What is a Krampus?

10:47.188 --> 10:48.690
He's, like,
this half‐goat demon

10:48.690 --> 10:50.608
that punishes misfit children
during the holiday season.

10:50.608 --> 10:52.110
So badass.

10:52.110 --> 10:53.653
If we're doing Krampus,
then I want the Yule Cat.

10:53.653 --> 10:54.696
Yule wha?

10:54.696 --> 10:55.738
My Grammy's
from Iceland,

10:55.738 --> 10:57.240
and that's
her favorite holiday story.

10:57.240 --> 10:58.992
The Yule Cat eats kids
who haven't received

10:58.992 --> 11:00.869
any new clothes to wear
before Christmas Eve.

11:00.869 --> 11:02.871
Okay, sounds
unnecessarily punitive,

11:02.871 --> 11:05.039
but tell Granny it's in.

11:05.039 --> 11:08.168
Ooh! Uh, can we add in Festivus,
the holiday for the rest of us?

11:08.168 --> 11:10.086
No!
That's from "Seinfeld."

11:10.086 --> 11:11.254
No, it's real now.

11:11.254 --> 11:13.548
My dad makes us gather
around the Festivus pole

11:13.548 --> 11:15.175
for the airing
of grievances.

11:15.175 --> 11:16.467
This sounds like
a lot of work.

11:16.467 --> 11:18.136
Why don't we just
go back to the original play?

11:18.136 --> 11:19.512
Okay,
I see what you're doing.

11:19.512 --> 11:22.056
You're suggesting
a bunch of lame‐butt holidays

11:22.056 --> 11:23.516
so I'll give up on Kwanzaa.

11:23.516 --> 11:25.935
Did you just call Diwali
a lame‐butt holiday?

11:25.935 --> 11:28.229
No, no, no! They're all equally
big in the butt department.

11:28.229 --> 11:31.399
Christmas and Hanukkah
and Kwanzaa and Diwali

11:31.399 --> 11:33.234
and the demon‐goat thing

11:33.234 --> 11:37.322
and your granny's Icelandic
snow cat who eats naked kids.

11:37.322 --> 11:38.573
[ School bell rings ]

11:38.573 --> 11:40.575
Okay. Is that the bell?
Well...

11:40.575 --> 11:42.744
Good luck, Uncle J.

11:42.744 --> 11:44.162
<i>While Felicia turned Kwanzaa</i>

11:44.162 --> 11:45.997
<i>into an avalanche of holidays</i>
<i>for Glascott,</i>

11:45.997 --> 11:47.749
<i>CB faced his own disaster.</i>

11:47.749 --> 11:48.875
Why are you here?

11:48.875 --> 11:50.752
To buy a Christmas present
for Lainey.

11:50.752 --> 11:52.045
It's a platypus.

11:52.045 --> 11:53.296
What about the Barry‐cuda?

11:53.296 --> 11:54.672
Decoy.

11:54.672 --> 11:57.050
Only problem is, Detroit <i>loves</i>
their Beanie Babies,

11:57.050 --> 11:58.676
and they're all tapped out.

11:58.676 --> 12:00.803
Luckily, my lazy‐eyed
nerd brother, Adam,

12:00.803 --> 12:04.015
says <i>this</i> store
always has the goods.

12:04.015 --> 12:05.225
Wow.
That's so weird.

12:05.225 --> 12:07.185
That platypus is
the exact same Beanie Baby

12:07.185 --> 12:08.436
I'm here to get for CB.

12:08.436 --> 12:10.563
It's not weird.
It's actually very normal.

12:10.563 --> 12:12.607
Can you be a pal
and sit this one out?

12:12.607 --> 12:13.900
I'm doing this for love.

12:13.900 --> 12:16.945
Again, so weird, because CB is
also doing it for love.

12:16.945 --> 12:19.030
You know what? We don't have to
talk about it anymore.

12:19.030 --> 12:21.157
In fact, you know what?
We should go.
Go?!

12:21.157 --> 12:23.159
But you said this Beanie Baby
is the only way to get

12:23.159 --> 12:25.536
the girl you love to realize
she's dating the wrong person.

12:25.536 --> 12:26.663
Aw, man!

12:26.663 --> 12:27.997
She's got a boyfriend?

12:27.997 --> 12:29.123
Please don't root for me.

12:29.123 --> 12:30.375
Sounds like a total dingus.

12:30.375 --> 12:32.418
Hey, guys, can we open
that [bleep] gate?

12:32.418 --> 12:34.254
[ "Eye of the Tiger" plays ]
Mellor: It's go time!

12:34.254 --> 12:35.797
Go, go, go, go.
Go, go.

12:35.797 --> 12:36.923
Run, Rick, run!

12:36.923 --> 12:38.258
[ Music slows, stops ]

12:38.258 --> 12:40.260
[ Screams ]
My unbreakable ankle!

12:40.260 --> 12:41.427
We need a doctor!

12:41.427 --> 12:42.762
Incoming stat!

12:42.762 --> 12:44.764
Leave me!
Go get your Patti the Platty!

12:44.764 --> 12:47.058
Your ankle's swelling!
I've got to get you to the ER!

12:47.058 --> 12:48.643
[ Grunts ]
Sneaky strong.

12:48.643 --> 12:50.395
Make way!

12:50.395 --> 12:53.189
I've got an injured
American gym teacher!

12:53.189 --> 12:55.942
I'm helping, too.
I have his shoe.

12:55.942 --> 12:58.945
<i>While Coach was in bad shape,</i>
<i>Glascott and Wilma came to see</i>

12:58.945 --> 13:00.697
<i>how the all‐inclusive</i>
<i>holiday show was shaping up.</i>

13:00.697 --> 13:02.991
♪ Jingle bells, jingle bells ♪

13:02.991 --> 13:05.118
♪ Jingle all the way ♪

13:05.118 --> 13:06.911
♪ Seven days of Kwanzaa ♪

13:06.911 --> 13:08.830
♪ Kwanzaa, eh ♪

13:08.830 --> 13:12.250
♪ Dreidel, dreidel, dreidel,
I made you out of clay ♪

13:12.250 --> 13:15.878
♪ Diwali's here
for five great nights ♪

13:15.878 --> 13:18.381
[ To tune of
"Eye of the Tiger" ]
♪ Box, Boxing Day ♪

13:18.381 --> 13:20.174
♪ A day to box ♪

13:20.174 --> 13:23.636
♪ Boxing Daaaaay ♪

13:23.636 --> 13:27.598
♪ It's the day of the boxing,
it's the Boxing Day ♪

13:27.598 --> 13:31.144
♪ But it's not
the "Rocky" kind of boxing ♪

13:31.144 --> 13:33.479
What's the deal
with Festivus?

13:33.479 --> 13:35.940
♪ It's when lords
give their servants ♪

13:35.940 --> 13:37.650
♪ New, shiny gifts ♪

13:37.650 --> 13:41.821
♪ In a box on a day,
so it's called ♪

13:41.821 --> 13:44.407
♪ Day of boxing ♪

13:44.407 --> 13:48.911
All hail Krampus,
horned king of holiday darkness!

13:48.911 --> 13:51.789
<i>While Glascott realized he may</i>
<i>have wrecked the holiday show,</i>

13:51.789 --> 13:54.125
<i>CB was hoping</i>
<i>Mellor's ankle</i> wasn't <i>wrecked.</i>

13:54.125 --> 13:56.753
I don't know why,
but I feel like this is
partially my fault.

13:56.753 --> 13:59.130
Maybe you feel that way
because every part of
this is your fault!

13:59.130 --> 14:01.924
I need a new ankle
because you wanted
a bean‐filled platypus.

14:01.924 --> 14:03.176
I would never
even have asked

14:03.176 --> 14:05.011
if I'd known
that Barry was gonna be there,

14:05.011 --> 14:06.387
getting the same
darn Beanie Baby

14:06.387 --> 14:07.388
for the same darn girl.

14:08.598 --> 14:09.640
Wait, what?
What?

14:09.640 --> 14:11.142
Darn girl who?
Who? What?

14:11.142 --> 14:11.893
Lainey who.

14:11.893 --> 14:13.019
Lainey who..what?

14:13.019 --> 14:14.228
You know who, what!

14:14.228 --> 14:15.855
Are you telling me
I need a new ankle

14:15.855 --> 14:18.066
because you wanted to
break up my friend and
the love of her life?

14:18.066 --> 14:20.443
Y‐Y‐Ye‐Yes.

14:20.443 --> 14:21.569
What is wrong with you?

14:21.569 --> 14:23.112
Lainey would never
leave Barry.

14:23.112 --> 14:24.655
That dude's the best.

14:24.655 --> 14:27.075
Yeah, well, everyone says that,
but I just don't see it.

14:27.075 --> 14:28.451
Well, you gotta
get to know him!

14:28.451 --> 14:29.452
I <i>do</i> know him.

14:29.452 --> 14:31.287
He's immature
and clueless and dopey,

14:31.287 --> 14:33.498
and, honestly,
I don't even understand

14:33.498 --> 14:35.416
how that assclown
became a doctor.

14:35.416 --> 14:38.252
Good news, Coach.
Took a peek at your file.

14:38.252 --> 14:41.005
Seems like the doctor on call
thought he saw a fracture,

14:41.005 --> 14:42.465
but the cortices
are intact,

14:42.465 --> 14:44.592
so it's just
a ligamentous problem.

14:44.592 --> 14:47.678
Okay. Those <i>are</i> the words
of a very skilled doctor.

14:47.678 --> 14:49.222
I know.

14:49.222 --> 14:51.516
You probably think I'm just
some clueless, dopey assclown.

14:51.516 --> 14:53.976
[ Chuckling ]
What? No.

14:53.976 --> 14:56.729
My whole life, I always made
a bad first impression.

14:56.729 --> 14:58.606
I get nervous
around new people,

14:58.606 --> 15:00.608
and then I overcompensate

15:00.608 --> 15:04.112
by calling myself Big Tasty
and rap and nunchuck.

15:04.112 --> 15:05.655
This is all
very self‐aware.

15:05.655 --> 15:06.989
All thanks to Lainey.

15:06.989 --> 15:09.700
She's the first person
I could be myself around.

15:09.700 --> 15:12.203
But now that we went
through this together,

15:12.203 --> 15:13.621
we're bros.

15:13.621 --> 15:15.748
Now you get to see
the real me.

15:15.748 --> 15:17.291
He good. I like.

15:17.291 --> 15:18.584
Thanks, CB.

15:18.584 --> 15:21.254
Anyway, it's just a bad sprain.
No need for surgery.

15:21.254 --> 15:23.256
Sweet Lord,
you saved my ankle's life!

15:23.256 --> 15:25.550
My ankle will never forget
this kindness, Doc Barry.

15:25.550 --> 15:27.135
Here.

15:27.135 --> 15:28.469
For the patient's helper.

15:28.469 --> 15:30.555
I'll go get you
discharged.

15:30.555 --> 15:31.806
You were saying?

15:31.806 --> 15:32.765
[ Inhales deeply ]

15:32.765 --> 15:34.308
I see it now.

15:34.308 --> 15:36.644
That amazing bastard is
the best guy ever.

15:36.644 --> 15:38.229
Why didn't you just tell me
this was about Lainey?

15:38.229 --> 15:40.064
You could've avoided
this whole mess.

15:40.064 --> 15:43.484
I'm sorry. I guess I just wanted
to believe that I had a shot.

15:43.484 --> 15:44.902
But I get it now.

15:44.902 --> 15:46.279
It's time to move on.

15:46.279 --> 15:49.532
♪♪

15:51.951 --> 15:54.537
<i>As Glascott was making</i>
<i>some last‐minute changes</i>

15:54.537 --> 15:55.621
<i>to his show,</i>
<i>I had a few of my own.</i>

15:55.621 --> 15:57.707
Okay, I stayed up all night
writing a few songs,

15:57.707 --> 15:59.625
but we're good to go
on Australian Christmas.

15:59.625 --> 16:00.960
Australian what's happening?

16:00.960 --> 16:01.961
You didn't hear?

16:01.961 --> 16:03.713
Ronnie's super upset

16:03.713 --> 16:05.381
'cause we so cruelly left out
the holiday of his people.

16:05.381 --> 16:07.717
Ronnie's from South Philly, and
his parents own a hoagie shop.

16:07.717 --> 16:09.302
There's no way
he's Australian.

16:09.302 --> 16:10.720
Not to mention,
Australian Christmas

16:10.720 --> 16:12.430
is just Christmas.

16:12.430 --> 16:14.223
Classic Wilma ‐‐
so closed‐minded.

16:14.223 --> 16:15.975
Thankfully,
Felicia came directly to me

16:15.975 --> 16:17.059
so <i>I</i> could address
the issue.

16:17.059 --> 16:18.936
Felicia? Okay, wait.

16:18.936 --> 16:21.522
No, she's right.
I'm super closed‐minded.

16:21.522 --> 16:23.024
Please tell me all about

16:23.024 --> 16:25.109
how they celebrate the holidays
down under.

16:25.109 --> 16:27.320
Legend tells tale
of Kangy Dundee,

16:27.320 --> 16:29.530
the magical kangaroo
who hops into town,

16:29.530 --> 16:31.949
bringing with him a pouch full
of fresh shrimps off the barbie

16:31.949 --> 16:33.618
to give to
all the good boys and girls.

16:33.618 --> 16:35.244
And if you're naughty?
Then you get cold Vegemite

16:35.244 --> 16:36.662
with nary a cracker
to spread it on.

16:36.662 --> 16:37.914
[ Pitch pipe blows ]

16:37.914 --> 16:40.166
♪ They call him Kangy,
Kangy Dundee ‐‐ ♪

16:40.166 --> 16:42.335
Stop. Just stop.

16:42.335 --> 16:44.212
Felicia was messing with you
to get at <i>me.</i>

16:44.212 --> 16:45.671
How could you
not know this?

16:45.671 --> 16:48.382
'Cause ‐‐ I'm open‐minded
to all races and cultures,

16:48.382 --> 16:50.176
and I'm very bad
at this, John!

16:50.176 --> 16:51.886
So bad!

16:51.886 --> 16:53.638
Shame on you.

16:53.638 --> 16:55.556
Playing on
Lainey's desperate need

16:55.556 --> 16:58.517
to not be looked at
as an intolerant white lady.

16:58.517 --> 17:00.603
Yeah!
You were supposed to give up
when I said Boxing Day,

17:00.603 --> 17:01.938
but you refused
to back down.

17:01.938 --> 17:03.272
'Cause this is important.

17:03.272 --> 17:05.233
I know you want
to fly under the radar,

17:05.233 --> 17:07.276
but you can't live your life
like that.

17:07.276 --> 17:08.986
Why not?
<i>That's</i> why.

17:08.986 --> 17:09.987
Your grad‐school degree?

17:09.987 --> 17:11.322
Do you notice anything?

17:11.322 --> 17:13.032
It says your name
is...Andre?

17:13.032 --> 17:14.325
Exactly.

17:14.325 --> 17:15.910
When I went to Vassar,
our program only had

17:15.910 --> 17:17.536
two black grad students
in it ‐‐

17:17.536 --> 17:20.331
John Glascott
and Andre Jones.

17:20.331 --> 17:21.832
Let's just say
people got us confused.

17:21.832 --> 17:23.084
A lot.

17:23.084 --> 17:24.794
It felt easier
to just laugh it off

17:24.794 --> 17:25.920
than to speak up.

17:25.920 --> 17:27.755
But soon enough,
everyone actually thought

17:27.755 --> 17:29.340
that my name was Andre ‐‐

17:29.340 --> 17:31.050
even my professors

17:31.050 --> 17:32.802
who wrote my recommendation
to work here.

17:32.802 --> 17:34.428
Wait.

17:34.428 --> 17:36.889
You mean everyone <i>here</i>
thought your name was Andre?

17:36.889 --> 17:38.182
Only for 12 years.

17:38.182 --> 17:39.850
Then one day, I snapped.

17:39.850 --> 17:41.686
My name is not Andre.

17:41.686 --> 17:43.646
[ Voice breaking ]
My name is Jonathan!

17:43.646 --> 17:45.731
And I love you,
Lunch Lady Bernice!

17:45.731 --> 17:48.234
That day kick‐started
a whirlwind two weeks

17:48.234 --> 17:50.278
with a woman
that I was not ready for.

17:50.278 --> 17:51.696
While this is
a bummer story,

17:51.696 --> 17:53.322
what exactly does it
have to do with me?

17:53.322 --> 17:56.367
Because I want you to stand up
and be proud of who you are,

17:56.367 --> 17:58.661
not laugh it off
and fly under the radar,

17:58.661 --> 17:59.704
like I did.

17:59.704 --> 18:01.914
That makes sense.

18:01.914 --> 18:03.124
Well, doesn't matter now.

18:03.124 --> 18:05.126
We're going back
to our old Christmas concert,

18:05.126 --> 18:07.962
because our all‐inclusive show
is a disaster.

18:07.962 --> 18:10.590
[ "You Gotta Be" plays ]

18:10.590 --> 18:12.550
Maybe we can still
give it a shot.

18:12.550 --> 18:15.219
Just...with a tad less "Rocky"
and puffy Seinfeld shirts.

18:15.219 --> 18:17.555
It's fine. You don't
have to do Kwanzaa for me.

18:17.555 --> 18:18.806
I'm not.

18:18.806 --> 18:20.725
Look, I didn't want
to stand out,

18:20.725 --> 18:23.686
but if that leads
to me losing a part of myself,

18:23.686 --> 18:25.062
I'm not gonna
let that happen.

18:26.314 --> 18:27.690
And I'm also
part of the problem

18:27.690 --> 18:30.359
when I get all awkward
talking about this stuff.

18:30.359 --> 18:31.485
No more, sista.

18:31.485 --> 18:32.570
Don't.
No.

18:32.570 --> 18:34.655
Let's go spread
some holiday cheer, huh?

18:35.489 --> 18:36.991
Yeah.

18:36.991 --> 18:41.871
♪ Try and keep your head
up to the sky ♪

18:41.871 --> 18:44.415
♪ Lovers,
they may cause you tears ♪

18:44.415 --> 18:47.126
♪ Go ahead, release your fears ♪

18:47.126 --> 18:48.919
♪ Stand up and be counted ♪

18:48.919 --> 18:51.213
♪ Don't be ashamed to cry ♪

18:51.213 --> 18:52.632
♪ You gotta be... ♪

18:52.632 --> 18:54.508
<i>That night, we put on</i>
<i>the best holiday show</i>

18:54.508 --> 18:57.178
<i>the school had ever seen.</i>

18:57.178 --> 18:58.554
<i>Even though the idea was</i>

18:58.554 --> 19:00.765
<i>for everyone to learn</i>
<i>about our holidays,</i>

19:00.765 --> 19:03.351
<i>we all ended up learning</i>
<i>something more important.</i>

19:03.351 --> 19:04.769
♪ You gotta be cool ♪

19:04.769 --> 19:06.896
<i>When you set aside</i>
<i>your differences</i>

19:06.896 --> 19:09.690
<i>and learn to embrace them,</i>
<i>you can accomplish anything.</i>

19:09.690 --> 19:12.485
♪ All I know is,
love will save the day ♪

19:12.485 --> 19:15.196
♪ Herald what your mother said ♪

19:15.196 --> 19:17.698
Here ya go.
Fresh from the oven.

19:17.698 --> 19:20.326
I'm gonna get out of here,
give you guys some alone time.

